<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-strict.dtd">
<html xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><head>
    <title>CSS Test: Image shape on a left float</title>
    <link href="bjonesbe@adobe.com" rel="author" title="Bem Jones-Bey" />
    <link href="http://www.w3.org/TR/css-shapes-1/#shapes-from-image" rel="help" />
    <link href="http://www.w3.org/TR/css-shapes-1/#shape-outside-property" rel="help" />
    <link href="reference/shape-image-001-ref.xht" rel="match" />
    <meta content="ahem image" name="flags" />
    <meta content="This test verifies that a shape specified as a png image with 70% alpha is treated as if the image had no alpha." name="assert" />
    <style type="text/css">
        .container {
          position: relative;
          font-family: Ahem;
          font-size: 50px;
          line-height: 50px;
        }
        #test {
            width: 150px;
            color: rgb(0, 100, 0);
            background-color: black;
        }
        #image {
            float: left;
            width: 150px;
            height: 100px;
            shape-outside: url("support/left-half-rectangle-70.png");
        }
        #failure {
            width: 50px;
            height: 100px;
            background-color: red;
            position: absolute;
            top: 0px;
            right: 0px;
            z-index: -1;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <p>
        The test passes if you see a green rectangle, a black rectangle, and a green rectangle next to each other. There should be no red.
    </p>
    <div class="container" id="test">
        <div id="failure"></div>
        <div id="image">
            <img src="support/left-half-rectangle-70.png" />
        </div>
        X
        X
    </div>


</body></html>